<subSubSection lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="21" pageNumber="26" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="21.[811,1458,1364,2028]" box="[813,913,1364,1390]" pageId="21" pageNumber="26">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[811,1458,1364,2028]" pageId="21" pageNumber="26">
There are two specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dall" authorityYear="1900" box="[1136,1264,1395,1421]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Megathyrididae" genus="Argyrotheca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebratulida" pageId="21" pageNumber="26" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1136,1264,1395,1421]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="26">Argyrotheca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the MIRIKY collection from locality DW 3199 that externally resemble 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zezina" authorityYear="1987" box="[811,939,1459,1485]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Megathyrididae" genus="Argyrotheca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebratulida" pageId="21" pageNumber="26" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="species" species="angulata">
<emphasis box="[811,939,1459,1485]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="26">A. angulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as described by 
<bibRefCitation author="ZEZINA O. N." box="[1127,1288,1459,1485]" pageId="21" pageNumber="26" pagination="551 - 563" refId="ref21959" refString="ZEZINA O. N. 1987. - Brachiopods collected by BENTHEDI- Cruise in the Mozambique Channel. Bulletin du Museum national d'Histoire naturelle, 4 serie, section A, 9: 551 - 563." type="journal article" year="1987">Zezina (1987)</bibRefCitation>
from the 
<collectingCountry name="Mozambique" pageId="21" pageNumber="26">Mozambique</collectingCountry>
Channel. However, while both our specimens resemble the single specimen of Zezina’s in being markedly wider than long and having similar ornament, they show a very distinctive internal feature of ventro-laterally directed expansions or “prongs” emanating from the dorsal median septum (
<figureCitation box="[1005,1086,1650,1676]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="22.[132,143,1705,1723]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1659]" captionTargetId="figure-59@22.[132,1455,206,1663]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIG. 14. — A-J, Argyrotheca cf. angulata Zezina, 1987, North-West Madagascar, West of Cap d’Ambre, MIRIKY, stn DW 3199, 527-652 m: A-E, complete specimen (MNHN IB-2013-80), dorsal view (A); B-E, inner,oblique, tilted anterior views of dorsal valve, and enlargement (E) of septum and lateral outgrowths; F, inner view of ventral valve; G-J, complete specimen (MNHN IB-2013-81), dorsal view (G) and enlargement of umbonal part to show details of the beak; I, J, inner view of dorsal valve and enlargement (J) of tilted anterior view to show the prong; K, L, Argyrotheca jacksoni Cooper, 1973, South Madagascar, South Cap Sainte Marie, ATIMO VATAE, stn CP 3615, 284-286 m: K, inner of view of ventral valve (MNHN IB-2013-82); L, dorsal view of complete specimen (MNHN IB-2013-83). All SEMs. Scale bars: A-C, F-I, 1 mm; D, K, L, 500 µm; E, J, 200 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4578190" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4578190/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="26">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
B-E) that were not described in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zezina" authorityYear="1987" box="[815,936,1682,1708]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Megathyrididae" genus="Argyrotheca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebratulida" pageId="21" pageNumber="26" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="species" species="angulata">
<emphasis box="[815,936,1682,1708]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="26">A. angulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. These prongs are comparable to those described as “extravagant internal thickenings” in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cooper" authorityYear="1977" box="[1273,1391,1714,1741]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Megathyrididae" genus="Argyrotheca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebratulida" pageId="21" pageNumber="26" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="species" species="hewatti">
<emphasis box="[1273,1290,1714,1740]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="26">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1309,1391,1714,1740]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="26">hewatti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Gulf of Mexico by 
<bibRefCitation author="COOPER G. A." box="[1081,1315,1746,1772]" pageId="21" pageNumber="26" pagination="1 - 211" refId="ref19462" refString="COOPER G. A. 1977. - Brachiopods from the Caribbean Sea and adjacent waters. Studies in Tropical Oceanography 14: 1 - 211." type="journal article" year="1977">Cooper (1977: 111)</bibRefCitation>
. Similar but smaller-scale outgrowths are known for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Risso" baseAuthorityYear="1826" box="[1275,1393,1778,1804]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Terebratulidae" genus="Terebratula" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebratulida" pageId="21" pageNumber="26" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="species" species="cuneata">
<emphasis box="[1275,1393,1778,1804]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="26">A. cuneata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Mediterranean (see 
<bibRefCitation author="ALVAREZ F. &amp; BRUNTON C. H. C. &amp; LONG S. L." box="[1085,1314,1810,1839]" pageId="21" pageNumber="26" pagination="289 - 297" refId="ref18623" refString="ALVAREZ F., BRUNTON C. H. C. &amp; LONG S. L. 2008 a. - Megathyrididae loop: a simple complication. Fossils and Strata 54: 289 - 297." type="journal article" year="2008">
Álvarez 
<emphasis box="[1176,1232,1810,1836]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="26">et al.</emphasis>
2008a
</bibRefCitation>
, b for list of authors and discussion of this feature). These outgrowths, which are formed of secondary fibres (
<figureCitation box="[1253,1356,1873,1900]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="22.[132,143,1705,1723]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1659]" captionTargetId="figure-59@22.[132,1455,206,1663]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIG. 14. — A-J, Argyrotheca cf. angulata Zezina, 1987, North-West Madagascar, West of Cap d’Ambre, MIRIKY, stn DW 3199, 527-652 m: A-E, complete specimen (MNHN IB-2013-80), dorsal view (A); B-E, inner,oblique, tilted anterior views of dorsal valve, and enlargement (E) of septum and lateral outgrowths; F, inner view of ventral valve; G-J, complete specimen (MNHN IB-2013-81), dorsal view (G) and enlargement of umbonal part to show details of the beak; I, J, inner view of dorsal valve and enlargement (J) of tilted anterior view to show the prong; K, L, Argyrotheca jacksoni Cooper, 1973, South Madagascar, South Cap Sainte Marie, ATIMO VATAE, stn CP 3615, 284-286 m: K, inner of view of ventral valve (MNHN IB-2013-82); L, dorsal view of complete specimen (MNHN IB-2013-83). All SEMs. Scale bars: A-C, F-I, 1 mm; D, K, L, 500 µm; E, J, 200 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4578190" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4578190/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="26">Fig. 14E</figureCitation>
), do not seem to be muscle platforms and at present their function is unknown. Because of the small number of specimens at our disposal we are reluctant to describe our form as a new species at this stage.
</paragraph>
